    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Ecc&egrave; quoties et quomodo humanam Livij prudentiam, divina redarguit Augustini sapientia. Singularis parallelismus: 
                        et perinsigne discrimen inter cives Romana[e,] divina[e]q[ue] Civitatis. Vtriusq[ue] Politismus egregius, et plaerumq[ue] fortunatus: 
                        sed divinus tandem et firmior durat et foelicior quam humanus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Look how and how often Augustine’s divine wisdom refutes Livy’s sagacity. A remarkable parallelism and a most striking distinction between 
                the citizens of Rome and those of the divine City. The political perspectives of both are excellent and mostly successful, yet in the end the divine 
                one lasts more securely and propitiously than the human one.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Prima Romuli Legatio.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Romulus’ first embassy.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Pro associatione, et confoederatione, novo principi necessaria. Eadem A[e]nea[e] politica praxis l. 8. A[e]neidos.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Aeneas"/>
                    <book title="Aeneid"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Necessary for a new leader in the interest of an alliance and covenant. Aeneas pursued the same political exercise in bk 8 of the Aeneid.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Strategema raptarum Sabinarum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The strategem of the rape of the Sabine women.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>braue Romulus. [the] glorious veine of [the] worthiest Romans, euen of the most excellent Scipio himself. i[nfr]a, 404.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>De raptu Sabinarum, alijsq[ue] iniquitatibus, quae in Civitate Romana, etiam laudatis vigu&ecirc;re temporibus. 
                        August. l. 2. c. 17. de Civit. Quo iure, quo foedere Romani obtinuerint prima coniugia. Idem l. 3. c. 13.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Of the rape of the Sabine women and other iniquities which flourished in the city of Rome even in the days when she was most highly esteemed: Augustine, City of God, bk. 2, c. 17. 
                By what right or treaty the Romans obtained their first wives: idem, bk. 3, c. 14.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
